    "created_at": "2015-11-25T22:53:41Z",
    "updated_at": "2015-11-25T22:53:41Z",
    "body": "On Mac OS X, applications can be hidden and windows can be hidden. In the first case (`Cmd-H`), the entire application is hidden, which isn't the same as hiding all of the windows of the application. Clicking the notification un-hides the application and brings it to the foreground (it should show your app in the menu bar), but doesn't do anything to the windows.\n\nMac OS X doesn't require that applications have any open windows, so it's totally up to you to listen for the app to be activated and show the window you want to ensure is visible if it's been hidden. I think in Mac OS X's `NSWindowController`, you can specify that your app should \"Show on Activate\", but it's an opt-in thing.\n\nI think it's probably best for this to be implemented by listening for the `activate` event and showing the app's main window. Our app has several windows hidden most of the time, and we wouldn't want them to show automatically when it was brought to the foreground.\n"
  },
